1. Where did training fail due to structure?

Deep sigmoid network (10-layer) struggled.

Gradients became very small in early layers.

Validation accuracy stopped improving.

Structure prevented effective gradient flow.


2. Where did optimizer matter more than activation?

In CNN, activation was same (ReLU).

SGD was slow and unstable.

Adam converged faster and smoother.

So optimizer affected convergence more than activation.


3.  Where did activation matter more than depth?

Same depth (10 layers), different activations.

Sigmoid degraded.

ReLU trained properly.

Activation influenced learning more than adding layers.


4.️ What causes gradient shrinkage?

Backprop multiplies derivatives layer by layer.

Sigmoid derivative is small.

Repeated multiplication → gradient becomes near zero.

Early layers stop learning.


5. Why does CNN generalize better than dense?

Parameter sharing.

Fewer parameters.

Preserves spatial structure.

Strong inductive bias.


️6. Why does dropout reduce overfitting?

Randomly disables neurons.

Prevents co-adaptation.

Acts like model averaging.

Reduces train–validation gap.


7.️ When does depth hurt test performance?

When model capacity > data.

Training accuracy high but validation low.

Overfitting increases.

Vanishing gradients in deep sigmoid.


8. Did validation always predict test performance correctly?

Mostly close.

Small differences observed.

Validation is an estimate, not exact.

Depends on data split.
